1466":"1466","1388":"1388","about 1433":"about 1433","17 January 1466":"17 January 1466","1483":"1483","12 October 1483":"12 October 1483","1390":"1390","Sulham, Berkshire, England":"Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","Tilehurst, Berkshire, England":"Tilehurst, Berkshire, England","Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bushnell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Bushnells Green in Bucklebury (Berkshire), early recorded as <i>Bushenell</i> or <i>Busshendhill</i>.","History: Francis Bushnell came to New Haven, CT, in 1639, and was a founder of Guilford, CT."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":41,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Bushnell was born in 1414, in Sulham, Berkshire, England, his father, Richard Bushnell, was 27 and his mother, Isabel Bushnell, was 24. He married Alice Maud Webb about 1433. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 12 October 1483, in Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1414–12 October 1483":"1414–12. oktoober 1483","1414–1483":"1414–1483","1414–1466":"1414–1466","1434–1524":"1434–1524","1388–Male":"1388–Surnud","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1414":"1414","1524":"1524","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1466":"1466","1388":"1388","about 1433":"umbes 1433","17 January 1466":"17. jaanuar 1466","1483":"1483","12 October 1483":"12. oktoober 1483","1390":"1390","Sulham, Berkshire, England":"Sulham, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tilehurst, Berkshire, England":"Tilehurst, Berkshire, England","Sulham, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Sulham, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1414–12 October 1483":"1414–12. lokakuuta 1483","1414–1483":"1414–1483","1414–1466":"1414–1466","1434–1524":"1434–1524","1388–Male":"1388–Kuollut","1390–Female":"1390–Kuo